<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">

<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>
        <%= title %> | Forecasting Recessions
    </title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="/css/style.css">
</head>

<body>
    <%- include('partials/header') %>

        <main>
    <h1>Exploratory Data Analysis</h1>

    <section>
        <h2>1. Dataset Overview</h2>
        <p>
            The data were collected through API access from two primary sources. From Federal Reserve
            Economic Data (FRED), we obtained the unemployment rate, inflation rate, federal funds
            interest rate, and the U.S. recession indicator. From Yahoo Finance, we collected financial
            market indicators including the S&P 500 index, the VIX volatility index, and gold prices.
        </p>

        <p>
            The analysis primarily uses data beginning in 1968 for unemployment, inflation, interest
            rates, and the S&P 500 index. However, VIX and gold price data are only available starting
            from 1990. As a result, analyses involving these two variables are restricted to the period
            from 1990 onward.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>2. Data Cleaning and Preparation</h2>
        <p>
            The recession indicator is recorded monthly and serves as the target variable for this
            analysis. Because the original datasets were reported at different frequencies including
            daily, monthly, and yearly, each dataset was converted to a consistent monthly frequency
            using end-of-month values.
        </p>

        <p>
            Two primary dataframes were constructed. The first includes unemployment, inflation,
            interest rates, and the recession indicator. The second includes financial indicators
            including the S&P 500, VIX, and gold prices beginning in 1990. Rows with missing values
            were removed to ensure aligned observations.
        </p>

        <p>
            The final cleaned dataset extends through 2024, and no duplicate or inconsistent records
            were identified.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>3. Summary Statistics and Normalization</h2>

        <p>
            The dataset contains variables measured on very different scales. For example, the S&P 500
            is measured in large index values, while unemployment and inflation are measured in
            percentages. Direct comparison between these variables would therefore be misleading.

            To ensure fair comparison, all indicators were normalized using Z-score normalization, 
            which transforms each variable to have a mean of zero and a standard deviation of one. 
            This allows each indicator to be interpreted relative to its own historical average and variability, 
            preventing larger-scale variables from dominating the visualizations.
        </p>

        <p>
            A correlation heatmap was also created to examine the relationships between all economic and financial indicators.
        </p>

        <figure>
            <img src="\images\correlation-of-financial-economic-indicator.png" alt="Correlation heatmap">
            <figcaption>Figure 1. Correlation heatmap of economic and financial indicators.</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <p>
            Based on the heatmap, we observe that <b>inflation and interest rates have a strong positive correlation (0.69).</b> 
            This is because central banks raise interest rates to control rising inflation. When inflation increases, 
            the Federal Reserve typically increases rates to reduce spending and slow price growth. The <b>S&P 500 has a negative 
            correlation with interest rates (-0.46).</b> Higher interest rates increase borrowing costs for companies and reduce 
            future earnings expectations, which can lower stock prices. The <b>S&P 500 also has a negative correlation with unemployment 
            (-0.37)</b> and <b>positive correlation with gold (0.41).</b>
        </p>

        <p>
            Overall, while the correlations are moderate rather than strong, they reflect logical economic relationships between monetary policy, 
            economic conditions, and financial markets.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>4. Visualization Analysis</h2>

        <p>
            To better understand indicator behavior around recession periods, two normalized line
            graphs were created. The first graph includes unemployment, inflation, and interest rates,
            while the second graph includes the S&P 500, VIX, and gold prices.
        </p>

        <figure>
            <img src="\images\economic-indicators-time-series-plot.png" alt="Economic indicators graph">
            <figcaption>Figure 2. Normalized trends of unemployment, inflation, and interest rates.</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <figure>
            <img src="\images\financial-indicators-time-series-plot.png" alt="Financial indicators graph">
            <figcaption>Figure 3. Normalized trends of S&P 500, VIX, and gold prices.</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <p>
            The long-term line graphs show that during the first four recessions (1970s–early 1980s), 
            <b>inflation and interest rates increased before recession.</b> In contrast, during the later 
            recessions (2001, 2008, 2020), both generally declined before recession, indicating that patterns 
            vary across economic periods. Unemployment typically remains stable before recession and rises afterward, 
            suggesting it behaves as a lagging indicator. Since line graphs do not measure the size of changes, heatmaps 
            were created to show percentage changes 3, 6, 12, and 24 months before each recession.

        </p>

        <figure>
            <img src="\images\indicator-changes-heatmap-1968–2024.png" alt="Indicator heatmap 1968">
            <figcaption>Figure 4. Indicator percentage changes before recessions (1968–2024).</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <p>
            The heatmap covering 1968 to 2024 suggests the following:
        </p>

        <ul>
            <li><b>Unemployment</b>: Typically rises after recession begins, not before. This supports the idea that it is not a strong early warning indicator.</li>
            <li><b>Inflation</b>: Shows a mixed pattern, with no consistent direction before recessions.</li>
            <li><b>Interest Rate</b>: Behavior varies across periods because it reflects policy responses rather than direct economic stress.</li>
            <li><b>S&P 500</b>: Often declines 3 to 6 months before recession. However, 12- and 24-month patterns are less consistent.</li>
        </ul>

        <p>
            These results suggest that recession patterns depend on the underlying cause of the downturn.
        </p>

        <figure>
            <img src="\images\indicator-changes-heatmap-1990–2024.png" alt="Indicator heatmap 1990">
            <figcaption>Figure 5. Indicator percentage changes before recessions (1990–2024).</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <p>
            Since the 1990 recession began in August 1990 and financial data started in January 1990, it is excluded from the 12- and 24-month windows due to insufficient prior data.
            From this heatmap we have observed the followings:
        </p>

        <ul>
            <li><b>S&P 500</b>: Gradually decreases before most recessions.</li>
            <li><b>VIX</b>: Spikes sharply as recession approaches, especially in the short term.</li>
            <li><b>Gold</b>: Does not show a consistent pattern across recessions.</li>
        </ul>

        <p>
            These findings indicate that market-based indicators may provide earlier signals than macroeconomic variables.
        </p>

    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>5. Preliminary Insights and Hypothesis Formation</h2>

        <ul>
            <li>The S&P 500 often declines 3 to 6 months before recession.</li>
            <li>VIX tends to increase sharply near recession onset.</li>
            <li>Inflation and interest rate patterns vary across economic periods.</li>
        </ul>

        <p>
            These results suggest that financial market indicators, particularly stock performance and
            volatility, may provide stronger short-term signals of upcoming recessions than traditional
            macroeconomic indicators.
        </p>
    </section>
</main>

        <%- include('partials/footer') %>
</body>

</html>